Analysis of bookmaker peformance based on “odds” and “match results”

In the homework we tried to analyze the performance of the bookmakers based on odds they gavefor matches. This operation repeated for five different bookmakers.

Secondly, we looked the performance of the selected bookmakers over years to evaluate how good they are at determining odds.

Lastly, as you know the bookmakers change their odds constantly, the changes have meaning in it.To find out number of the odds plotted against total score due to a hypothesis that being predictable means having many goals in the match so number off odds should be less. In other words odd makers does not need to update the odds multiple times.

Task1.a Are bookmakers good at determining over under odds?

The homework will require using specific packages so these packages recalled first.

library(data.table)
library(anytime)
library(plotrix) # Used to plot graph with two(2) y axes

To start the analysis, the data is read using relevant functions and data tables are created.

odd_details=readRDS("/Users/alifurkanyavuz/Downloads/odd_details.rds")
matches=readRDS("/Users/alifurkanyavuz/Downloads/matches.rds")
DT_matches=data.table(matches)
DT_odd_details=data.table(odd_details)

The question asking to look at over/under bets and focusing the threshold “2.5” is suggested so the table is filtered accordingly.

DT_odd_details=DT_odd_details[betType=="ou" &totalhandicap== 2.5]

The date format in the data is not easy to interpret so the anytime package used to convert this format to the real date format. This operation is carried out on both odds and matches data tables.In addition Year column is added to matches data table because we will need it in the second part of the question.

DT_matches[,match_time:=anytime(date)]
DT_odd_details[,match_time:=anytime(date)]
DT_matches[,Year:=year(match_time)]

To be able to calculate probabilities we need to make use of score data so, score column is separated in to two as HomeScore and AwayScore then their type is changed to numeric to carry out calculations. Sum_score column is created because to be able decide over/under cases we need this data.

DT_matches[,c("HomeScore","AwayScore"):= tstrsplit(score,":")]
DT_matches[,HomeScore:=as.numeric(HomeScore)]
DT_matches[,AwayScore:=as.numeric(AwayScore)]
DT_matches[,Sum_score:=(HomeScore+AwayScore)]

Due to the fact that we are focusing on the matches finished with score more than 2.5 we used IsOver as a binary variable which is “1”" if the match result is bigger than 2.5 and “0” if it is less than 2.5. But some of the points is not available so we removed these data points by complete.cases function.

DT_matches[,IsOver:=0]
DT_matches[Sum_score>2,IsOver:=1]
DT_matches=DT_matches[complete.cases(DT_matches)] # removes NAs

As you know the odds data have multiple odds for the same match because bookmakers are updating. To make analysis we need to find initial and final odds. So, first the odds are ordered then we selected the initial and final odds then stored this information as data tables to look performance by initial and final odds.

DT_odd_details=DT_odd_details[order(matchId, oddtype,bookmaker,date)]

DT_odd_details_initial=DT_odd_details[,list(start_odd=odd[1]), by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]
DT_odd_details_final=DT_odd_details[,list(final_odd=odd[.N]), by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]

As suggested in the homework we focused on different bookmakers one by one so, five(5) bookmakers are selected randomly to analyze 1. Pinnacle 2. bwin 3. Betsafe 4. Unibet 5. youwin the code will be provided for one of the bookmakers for initial odds case only. Because the code is same for the final odds case and other bookmakers.

To start analysis one by one, the bookmaker “Pinnacle” is filtered, and the table turned into wide table. We have to merge the odd details with matches later using match IDs.

innacle_ou=DT_odd_details_initial[bookmaker=="Pinnacle"]

pinnacle_wide=dcast(pinnacle_ou,matchId~oddtype,value.var ='start_odd')

Matches data is merged with the wide table of the odd details. So a table which has scores and years by match ID is created.

merged_matches_pinnacle=merge(DT_matches,pinnacle_wide,by="matchId")

The probabilities are computed by inversing the odds.

merged_matches_pinnacle[,prob_over:=(1/over)]
merged_matches_pinnacle[,prob_under:=(1/under)]

Total probability is computed by summing over and under probabilities but the sum is bigger than one(1) due to bookmakers margin so it is normalized.

merged_matches_pinnacle[,total_prob:=(prob_over+prob_under)]

merged_matches_pinnacle[,prob_over:=prob_over/total_prob]

merged_matches_pinnacle[,prob_under:=prob_under/total_prob]

The data is discretized, so we can interpret the data better and some bins are merged because the probabilities were unreasonable and sample sizes are smaller. The process is merged_matches _pinnacle is created first, and then the probabilities and sample sizes are evaluated based on the problematic bins. Lastly,some bins are merged.

cutpoints=seq(0,1,0.025)
cutpoints
cutpoints=cutpoints[-c(15,27)]
merged_matches_pinnacle[,odd_cut:=cut(prob_over,cutpoints)]

Summary table created in which we have calculated empirical over(real results) and probabilistic over(implified probabilities). Then, the table is ordered based on the bins.

summary_table_pinnacle=merged_matches_pinnacle[,list(empirical_over=mean(IsOver),
                                   probabilistic_over=mean(prob_over),.N),
                                   by=list(odd_cut)]
summary_table_pinnacle_initial=summary_table_pinnacle[order(odd_cut)]

The plot is created to show empirical probabilities versus implied probabilities, because the probability scale is 0-1 the limits are 0-1. X=Y line is created for interpretation purposes because if book makers are good enough, we expect that the probabilities are on the x=y line.

plot(summary_table_pinnacle_initial[,list(empirical_over,probabilistic_over)],
     main="pinnacle_performance_initial",
     xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1))
abline(0,1,col='red')

Tofind final odds and other bookmaker data same code is used, so we directly continue with the plots of the results.

Plots of the selected bookmakers.

Pinnacle Graphs- Based on Initial and Final odds

The points are around x=y line which mean the bookmaker is good at determining odds but the initial odds are more dispersed than the final odds. They improved their ability to predict the result in the final odds. As can be seen on the graph they are mostly near x=y line

bwin Graphs- Based on Initial and Final odds

This bookmaker is mostly good at determining the odds. All points is in line with x=y. But there is only one outlier in the final odds graph.

Betsafe Graphs- Based on Initial and Final odds

The betsafe’s initial predictions are better than their final ones. Because they are more in line with x=y line. There is no big difference between initial and final odds.

Unibet Graphs- Based on Initial and Final odds

Unibet performance is mostly better in final odds than the initial odds, but they still have problems with bins around 0.4 and 0.8 because they are not in line with x=y.

youwin Graphs- Based on Initial and Final odds

Youwin was better at prediction when we look from initial odds perspective, but their predictions are worsened with final odds. As you can see there are more deviations on the final graph.

Bins are created, and some bins are merged based on over probabilities and distribution of the number of matches

odd_cut_year=seq(0,1,0.05)
odd_cut_year=odd_cut_year[-c(9,15)]

odd_cut_year
merged_matches_betsafe_part_b[,odd_cut_year:=cut(prob_over,odd_cut_year)]

Task 2- Does odd changes have any information?

As suggested in the homework odd changes may have some information. The hypothesis is that the number off odds for the same match have information. This information is related with total match scores. It means if total score is smaller we expect less change in the odds because it is easier to predict the results and vice versa.

Youwin is selected for further investigation, so the data is filtered and unnecessary parts are removed. Date is converted to real date. The data is ordered based on matchId and time.

odds_bet_type_1X2=odd_details[betType=="1x2" &bookmaker=='youwin']
odds_bet_type_1X2=odds_bet_type_1X2[,totalhandicap:=NULL]
odds_bet_type_1X2[,match_time:=anytime(date)]
odds_bet_type_1X2=odds_bet_type_1X2[order(matchId,match_time)]

We need the information from matches data table, so the tables are merged based on unique match IDs.

merged_bet_type_1X2=merge(DT_matches,odds_bet_type_1X2,by="matchId")

The table includes the information of number of odds for the specific match under the column name “count” and total scores under the “sum_scores” column which have total score of the matches.

table_bet_type_1X2=merged_bet_type_1X2[,list(count=.N, sum_scores=mean(Sum_score)), 
                                       by=list(matchId)]

Plot is created to show the relation between number of changes and the total score.

plot(table_bet_type_1X2[,count,sum_scores], main='"youwin" Total Score vs Number of Odds',
                                            xlab='Total Score',ylab='Number of Odds')

As can be seen from the graph when the total score increases number of odds for these high score matches are decreases. Especially after total score five(5) you can see the decrease effectively.In other words bookmakers do not update their odds in high numbers becasue these matches are easy to predict.

In addition, you can see that the number of odds higher if the total score is smaller. It means these mathes are harde to predict so bookmakers need to make much more updates on odds.
